					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Let's start with some of my assumptions:<br /><br />1) This is essentially a daughterboard that plugs into where the maskrom normally is on the cartridge. You are using donor boards that have only one mask rom chip.<br /><br />2) You just load a (headerless) rom image onto the flash chip with no trickery involved. Just a straight copy in regards to A0..A22 on the flash chip.<br /><br />3) You let the board's address decode circuitry decide what to do with A15 and beyond coming from the SNES CPU, in regards to how it generates the \CE and \OE signals.<br /><br />4) If the spot for the chip is the smaller (shorter, less pins) version of the maskrom chip, you are tieing or pulling down these most significant address lines low (not leaving them floating) on your daugterboard (in relation to the flash chip).<br /><br /><br />Are any of these assumptions incorrect? Which of these are incorrect, and how should they be stated as to what you have?</div>

